\begin_layout Standard
Note that the information given to us is in terms of elasticities.
 Therefore, one step that we'll probably have to consider is turning these
 elasticities into the derivatives we've seen in section and in our problem
 sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 3a)
\series default
\shape default
 The correct concept is CV, which is equal to the change in wealth necessary
 for the consumer to achieve the same utility as before the price change
 after the price change has occurred.
 Thus, CV is the increase in wealth needed for the consumer, or the amount
 of wealth that a social planner has to give to the consumer (hence the
 minus sign for price increases), so that he or she is able to maintain
 the same utility level.
 Formally, CV is calculated as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CV=e(p^{1},u^{1})-e(p^{1},u^{0})=e(p^{0},u^{0})-e(p^{1},u^{0})=w-e(p^{1},u^{0}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 3b)
\series default
\shape default
 We use a linear approximation of the Hicksian demand curve.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Section Note 4.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Whenever we approximate a non-linear function, the first-step is to determine
 the point around which we want to approximate.
 Where is it going to be for this question?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\epsilon_{oil}^{p} & = & -2=\frac{dx}{dp}\cdot\frac{p}{x}=\frac{dx}{dp}\cdot\frac{10}{120}\Rightarrow\frac{dx}{dp}=-24\label{eq:price elasticity}\\
\epsilon_{oil}^{w} & = & 10=\frac{dx}{dw}\cdot\frac{w}{x}=\frac{dx}{dw}\cdot\frac{12,000}{120}\Rightarrow\frac{dx}{dw}=0.1\label{eq:wealth elasticity}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we use the Slutsky Equation and plug the results from equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:price elasticity"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wealth elasticity"

\end_inset

 to approximate the slope of the Hicksian at the 
\shape italic
old
\shape default
 price-wealth vector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dh}{dp}=\frac{dx}{dp}+\frac{dx}{dw}\cdot x=-24+0.1\cdot120=-12
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approximate change in the Hicksian demand is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta h & = & \frac{dh}{dp}\cdot\Delta p=-12\cdot2=-24\\
h(p=12,\vec{p}^{0},u^{0}) & \approx & h(10)+\frac{dh}{dp}\cdot\Delta p=120-24=96
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CV=-\frac{1}{2}\cdot2\cdot(96+120)=-216.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

