 that a consumer consumes.
 You'll learn more about this as we do partial equilibrium.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Then we can calculate the Laspeyres index as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
PI_{Laspeyres} & = & \frac{p'x^{0}+q'y^{0}}{px^{0}+qy^{0}}\\
 & = & \frac{12\cdot120+10,800}{10\cdot120+10,800}=1.02\\
 &  & (\because p^{0}x^{0}+q^{0}y^{0}=w\rightarrow10\cdot120+1\cdot y^{0}=12,000\rightarrow y^{0}=10,800)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Compensation=|PI_{Laspeyres}-1|\cdot w=240>|CV|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the Laspeyres Index generally results in over-compensation,
 since it does not take into account that the consumer facing a price increase
 on good 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 can re-optimize.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 3e)
\series default
\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
PI_{Paasche} & = & \frac{p'x'+q'y'}{px'+qy'}\\
 & = & \frac{12\cdot72+11,136}{10\cdot72+11,136}\approx1.0121\\
 &  & (\because p'x'+q'y'=w\rightarrow12\cdot72+1\cdot y'=12,000\rightarrow y'=11,136)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Compensation=|PI_{Paasche}-1|\cdot w\approx145.20<|CV|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Paasche Index generally results in under-compensation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Fisher Ideal Index takes the geometric mean of the Laspeyres and Paasche
