\begin_layout Standard
The relevant Bernoulli utility function is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)=cx^{\alpha},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 We know that agents/consumers are indifferent between the following lotteries
 over the respective outcomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
L_{1} & = & \left[\frac{1}{10^{6}},\,1-\frac{1}{10^{6}}\right];\,\, x_{1}=\left[\$10^{6},\,0\right]\\
L_{2} & = & \left[\frac{1}{2\cdot10^{6}},\,\frac{1}{20,000},\,1-\frac{1}{2\cdot10^{6}}-\frac{1}{20,000}\right];\,\, x_{2}=\left[\$10^{6},\,1000,\,0\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{1}\sim L_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question a and b)
\series default
\shape default
 Since agents are indifferent between the two lotteries, it must be the
 case that 
\begin_inset Formula $U(L_{1})=U(L_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Let's calculate each.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(L_{1})=\frac{1}{10^{6}}\cdot c(10^{6})^{\alpha}+\left(1-\frac{1}{10^{6}}\right)\cdot c(0)^{\alpha}=\frac{1}{10^{6}}\cdot c\cdot10^{6\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(L_{2})=\frac{1}{2\cdot10^{6}}\cdot c(10^{6})^{\alpha}+\frac{1}{20,000}\cdot c(10^{3})^{\alpha}+\left(1-\frac{1}{2\cdot10^{6}}-\frac{1}{20,000}\right)\cdot c(0)^{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting the two equations above equal to each other we see that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{10^{6}}\cdot c\cdot10^{6\alpha} & = & \frac{1}{2\cdot10^{6}}\cdot c\cdot10^{6\alpha}+\frac{1}{20,000}\cdot c\cdot10^{3\alpha}\\
\frac{1}{2\cdot10^{6}}\cdot c\cdot10^{6\alpha} & = & \frac{1}{20,000}\cdot c\cdot10^{3\alpha}\\
10^{3\alpha} & = & \frac{2\times10^{6}}{2\times10^{4}}=100\\
\therefore3\alpha & = & 2\\
\alpha & = & \frac{2}{3}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The important thing to notice is that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is not determined by the indifference between the two lotteries.
 Recall that positive linear transformations of the expected utility function
 represent the same preferences over lotteries.
 Why? Recall our discussion on how the expected utility function was a linear
 combination of the Bernoulli utility functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question c)
\series default
\shape default
 Let's solve by using the expected utilities.
 Define a new lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{3}=\left[p,\,1-p\right]$
\end_inset

 over the outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=\left[1000,\,0\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can calculate the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(L_{3})=p\cdot c\cdot10^{3\alpha}+\left(1-p\right)\cdot c\cdot0^{3\alpha}=100cp\,\left(\because\alpha=\frac{2}{3}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U(L_{3})=U(L_{1}),$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
100cp & = & \frac{1}{10^{6}}\cdot c\cdot10^{6\alpha}\\
p & = & \frac{1}{10^{4}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

