\begin_layout Subsection*
Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 1a) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 & \max_{x_{1},x_{2}}\left(x_{1}^{\frac{1}{2}}+x_{2}^{\frac{1}{2}}\right)^{2}\\
s.t & \vec{p}\cdot\vec{x}\leq w
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 1b)
\series default
\shape default
 Yes.
 The utility function above is strongly monotone (more is better), which
 implies Walras' Law.
 More formally, notice that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u}{\partial x_{1}}>0,\frac{\partial u}{\partial x_{2}}>0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 1c)
\series default
\shape default
 We need to set up the Lagrangian and solve, but before that is there anything
 we can do to make the function above more tractable? If you don't do this
 during the exam, you'd be stuck on this question for quite a while.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathfrak{L}(x_{1},x_{2},\lambda)=x_{1}^{\frac{1}{2}}+x_{2}^{\frac{1}{2}}-\lambda\left(p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}-w\right)\label{eq:Lagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We get the following first order conditions (if we assume an interior solution,
 which is a pretty good assumption given the fact that the objective function
 is concave):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\partial\mathfrak{L}(x_{1}^{*},x_{2}^{*},\lambda^{*})}{\partial x_{1}} & = & \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x_{1}^{*}}}-\lambda^{*}p_{1}=0\\
\frac{\partial\mathfrak{L}(x_{1}^{*},x_{2}^{*},\lambda^{*})}{\partial x_{2}} & = & \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x_{2}^{*}}}-\lambda^{*}p_{2}=0\\
\frac{\partial\mathfrak{L}(x_{1}^{*},x_{2}^{*},\lambda^{*})}{\partial\lambda} & = & p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}-w=0.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Solving the three equations for the three unknowns, we get the following
 (use the symmetry):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}^{*}(\vec{p},w)=\frac{w}{\left(p_{1}+\frac{p_{1}^{2}}{p_{2}}\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}^{*}(\vec{p},w)=\frac{w}{\left(p_{2}+\frac{p_{2}^{2}}{p_{1}}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

Both of which are homogeneous of degree 0 in the price-wealth vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we're asked to solve for the indirect utility function, which is an
 identity which takes prices and wealth as its arguments:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(\vec{p},w)=\left(\sqrt{x_{1}^{*}}+\sqrt{x_{2}^{*}}\right)^{2}=\left(\sqrt{\frac{w}{\left(p_{1}+\frac{p_{1}^{2}}{p_{2}}\right)}}+\sqrt{\frac{w}{\left(p_{2}+\frac{p_{2}^{2}}{p_{1}}\right)}}\right)^{2}=\frac{w(p_{1}+p_{2})}{p_{1}p_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 1d)
\series default
\shape default
