\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 1a)
\series default
\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 & \max_{x_{1},x_{2}}v(x_{1})+v(x_{2})\\
s.t & \vec{p}\cdot\vec{x}\leq w
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Question 1b)
\series default
\shape default
 We need to set up a Lagrangian.
 However, is there anything we can do to simplify the maximization? No.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{L}(x_{1},x_{2},\lambda)=v(x_{1})+v(x_{2})-\lambda\left(p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}-w\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We get the following first order conditions (Note that we know that there
 will be an interior solution here.
 Why? It is because of (one of) the Inada condition above,
\begin_inset Formula $v'(0)=\infty$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\partial\mathfrak{L}(x_{1}^{*},x_{2}^{*},\lambda^{*})}{\partial x_{1}} & = & v'(x_{1}^{*})-\lambda^{*}p_{1}=0\\
\frac{\partial\mathfrak{L}(x_{1}^{*},x_{2}^{*},\lambda^{*})}{\partial x_{2}} & = & v'(x_{2}^{*})-\lambda^{*}p_{2}=0\\
\frac{\partial\mathfrak{L}(x_{1}^{*},x_{2}^{*},\lambda^{*})}{\partial\lambda} & = & p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}-w=0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving for these equations to the extent possible, we have the following
 equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{v'(x_{1}^{*})}{v'(x_{2}^{*})}=\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}\label{eq:tangency}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}x_{1}^{*}+p_{2}x_{2}^{*}=w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
